  </figure>

  <div class="cosmos-legend">
    <div class="cosmos-legend__group">
      <h2 class="cosmos-legend__heading">The Center</h2>
      <p><strong>Ahvantir (the Material Plane)</strong> sits at the heart of the cosmos, wrapped in the churning band of the <strong>Elemental Chaos</strong> — the single tumultuous plane where fire, earth, water, and air blend without order. It is the only truly neutral plane of existence.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cosmos-legend__group">
      <h2 class="cosmos-legend__heading">The Inner Planes</h2>
      <p>Three realms encircle the Material Plane, each pressing close against it:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>The Dreaming</strong> — Nodd's sovereign domain, woven from the collective subconscious.</li>
        <li><strong>The Vast Green</strong> — the fey realm of raw emotion and untamed life; Ahvantir's plane of vibrant, positive energy.</li>
        <li><strong>The Faded Veil</strong> — the dark mirror of reality, wellspring of necrotic magic and shadow.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="cosmos-legend__group">
      <h2 class="cosmos-legend__heading">The Outer Planes — The Great Wheel</h2>
      <p>Sixteen outer planes ring the cosmos, arranged by alignment: the luminous <span class="cosmos-key cosmos-key--upper">Upper Planes</span> above, the <span class="cosmos-key cosmos-key--lower">Lower Planes</span> below, and the ordered <span class="cosmos-key cosmos-key--neutral">Neutral Planes</span> of pure law.</p>
      <div class="cosmos-wheel-cols">
        <div>
          <h3 class="cosmos-wheel-col__title">Upper</h3>
          <ol>
            <li>Mount Celestia</li>
            <li>Bytopia</li>
            <li>Elysium</li>
            <li>The Beastlands</li>
            <li>Arborea</li>
            <li>Ysgard</li>
            <li>Limbo</li>
          </ol>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="cosmos-wheel-col__title">Lower</h3>
          <ol>
            <li>Pandemonium</li>
            <li>The Abyss</li>
            <li>Carceri</li>
            <li>The Gray Waste (Hades)</li>
            <li>Gehenna</li>
            <li>The Nine Hells</li>
            <li>Acheron</li>
          </ol>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="cosmos-wheel-col__title">Neutral</h3>
          <ol>
            <li>Mechanus</li>
            <li>Arcadia</li>
          </ol>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="cosmos-legend__group">
      <h2 class="cosmos-legend__heading">The Space Between — Astral & Ethereal</h2>
      <p>Two overlapping fields fill the space between the planes, occupying the same expanse but operating on different levels:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>The Astral Sea</strong> — the structural scaffolding that holds the worlds and frameworks in place across the planes. It is the medium of true planar travel; to cross between worlds is to cross the Astral.</li>
        <li><strong>The Ethereal</strong> — the quieter medium where temporary processes and unseen features run in the background without disturbing the world. One steps into the Ethereal to observe or to glean information, rarely to journey.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="cosmos-legend__group">
      <h2 class="cosmos-legend__heading">The Ranjergon</h2>
      <p>Set apart from the rest of the cosmos in its own sphere, the <strong>Ranjergon</strong> is the Deific Plane — home to the gods, sealed away behind the <strong>Divine Gate</strong>. It touches none of the rings directly; the deities reach the mortal world only through permitted, indirect means.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cosmos-legend__group">
      <h2 class="cosmos-legend__heading">The Far Realm</h2>
      <p>Beyond the edges of everything, where the rules that hold the planes together no longer apply, presses the <strong>Far Realm</strong> — an alien wrongness that does not belong to the cosmos at all. It breaches at the margins, reaching tendrils and watching eyes inward. The ordered wheel of the planes holds against it; that it holds is not guaranteed forever.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

</div>
